WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:04.854 --> 00:00:06.770
MALE SPEAKER: This is
David Gelles, joining us

00:00:06.770 --> 00:00:09.920
from "The New York Times,"
where he's a business reporter.

00:00:09.920 --> 00:00:12.560
He's also an author
of "Mindful Work."

00:00:12.560 --> 00:00:15.500
And he's written
about his experiences

00:00:15.500 --> 00:00:18.520
with meditation, both
personally and in the workplace

00:00:18.520 --> 00:00:20.769
and many businesses
around the world.

00:00:20.769 --> 00:00:22.310
So without further
ado, here's David.

00:00:25.710 --> 00:00:26.860
DAVID GELLES: Thank you.

00:00:26.860 --> 00:00:29.097
Thanks, all, so much for
being here, really happy--

00:00:29.097 --> 00:00:30.930
you're all my guinea
pigs because I've never

00:00:30.930 --> 00:00:32.030
given this talk before.

00:00:32.030 --> 00:00:34.000
So bear with me, please.

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:37.430
So before I rattle on about
mindless and meditation,

00:00:37.430 --> 00:00:38.950
I thought it would
be appropriate

00:00:38.950 --> 00:00:42.230
if we just stopped for
just a second here.

00:00:42.230 --> 00:00:44.159
So if you would, you're
all being so diligent.

00:00:44.159 --> 00:00:45.700
You don't have your
smart phones out.

00:00:45.700 --> 00:00:47.535
You don't have
your laptops open.

00:00:47.535 --> 00:00:49.160
But if they are, if
you're hiding them,

00:00:49.160 --> 00:00:51.720
just put them away
for just a sec.

00:00:51.720 --> 00:00:55.710
And when I ring this bell, just
close your eyes if you would

00:00:55.710 --> 00:00:58.300
and focus on the sensation
of your breath, just

00:00:58.300 --> 00:01:01.200
the actual feeling of air moving
in and out of your nostril,

00:01:01.200 --> 00:01:02.750
wherever you feel it.

00:01:02.750 --> 00:01:04.720
Maybe it's your lungs
moving up and down,

00:01:04.720 --> 00:01:08.089
your chest inflating,
your diaphragm rising.

00:01:08.089 --> 00:01:09.380
And then here's the whole game.

00:01:09.380 --> 00:01:11.660
When you notice
your mind wander,

00:01:11.660 --> 00:01:13.440
just try to bring
your attention back

00:01:13.440 --> 00:01:15.440
to that physical
sensation of the breath.

00:01:15.440 --> 00:01:18.246
We'll just do it for
very short minute here.

00:01:18.246 --> 00:01:19.242
[BELL RINGING]

00:01:49.039 --> 00:01:51.580
If you find yourself wondering
when this is going to be over,

00:01:51.580 --> 00:01:54.000
just gently bring your
attention back to the breath.

00:02:00.383 --> 00:02:01.365
[BELL RINGING]

00:02:02.350 --> 00:02:07.320
OK, not so painful, I
hope, and like it or not,

00:02:07.320 --> 00:02:09.026
you're all now meditators.

00:02:09.026 --> 00:02:10.400
But before we get
started, I just

00:02:10.400 --> 00:02:13.400
want a quick show
of hands-- 0 to 10.

00:02:13.400 --> 00:02:15.490
Zero means you think
this is all hokum

00:02:15.490 --> 00:02:17.170
and you don't even
know why I'm up here.

00:02:17.170 --> 00:02:20.740
And meditation and business have
absolutely no place together.

00:02:20.740 --> 00:02:23.550
10 is you're already leading
the search inside yourself.

00:02:23.550 --> 00:02:26.000
I expect to see a 10 from
Don in the back, there.

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:30.004
So 0 to 10, just give me your
initial impressions-- 0s, 10s.

00:02:30.004 --> 00:02:31.170
OK, let me see what we have.

00:02:31.170 --> 00:02:32.330
We have sixes, sevens.

00:02:32.330 --> 00:02:33.800
I know I'm at Google.

00:02:33.800 --> 00:02:35.670
We have a five.

00:02:35.670 --> 00:02:37.190
OK, any twos or threes?

00:02:37.190 --> 00:02:39.010
No, you guys are so
welcome and receptive.

00:02:39.010 --> 00:02:41.620
OK, that's good.

00:02:41.620 --> 00:02:44.910
Those that are on the lower
end of the scale, I hear you.

00:02:44.910 --> 00:02:46.260
I was a skeptic at once, too.

00:02:46.260 --> 00:02:48.070
In fact, I'm a "New
York Times" journalist,

00:02:48.070 --> 00:02:50.530
so I'm paid to be cynical.

00:02:50.530 --> 00:02:54.280
But I hope what we'll find is
that that simple practice we

00:02:54.280 --> 00:02:58.420
just did is catching on in the
business world for good reason.

00:02:58.420 --> 00:03:01.180
At Goldman Sachs, a company
I cover pretty closely

00:03:01.180 --> 00:03:03.780
for "The New York Times," a
board member, Bill George,

00:03:03.780 --> 00:03:05.960
is actually espousing the
virtues of meditation.

00:03:05.960 --> 00:03:08.090
And traders and
investment bankers

00:03:08.090 --> 00:03:10.510
are practicing mindfulness,
trying to get an edge.

00:03:10.510 --> 00:03:14.610
At Facebook-- a cross-town
rival of your guys'-- they have

00:03:14.610 --> 00:03:17.017
actually retooled some of
their algorithms to try to make

00:03:17.017 --> 00:03:18.600
the social network
more compassionate.

00:03:18.600 --> 00:03:21.210
They have compassion
research days.

00:03:21.210 --> 00:03:22.890
You guys might want
to catch up there.

00:03:22.890 --> 00:03:26.952
At General Mills,
there's a meditation room

00:03:26.952 --> 00:03:28.660
in every building on
the corporate campus

00:03:28.660 --> 00:03:31.880
in the middle of the Midwest,
in Minneapolis, Minnesota.

00:03:31.880 --> 00:03:33.850
And it's not just business.

00:03:33.850 --> 00:03:36.500
In health care, doctors,
nurses, and patients

00:03:36.500 --> 00:03:38.720
are all finding value in
mindfulness and meditation

00:03:38.720 --> 00:03:39.909
for one reason or another.

00:03:39.909 --> 00:03:41.450
Doctors and nurses
find it makes them

00:03:41.450 --> 00:03:43.820
more resilient for these
long 12 hour shifts.

00:03:43.820 --> 00:03:47.320
And patients are discovering
that mindfulness and meditation

00:03:47.320 --> 00:03:49.360
might not make the
pain go away, but it

00:03:49.360 --> 00:03:52.060
can help them manage
their suffering.

00:03:52.060 --> 00:03:55.980
Students as well,
teachers also-- teachers

00:03:55.980 --> 00:03:58.910
find that mindfulness
can help them

00:03:58.910 --> 00:04:00.570
deal with rambunctious
little children.

00:04:00.570 --> 00:04:04.466
And students, younger and
even college students,

00:04:04.466 --> 00:04:06.840
are actually-- there are
studies that show this-- finding

00:04:06.840 --> 00:04:09.510
that mindfulness and meditation
can actually improve their test

00:04:09.510 --> 00:04:13.030
scores, help them be
more focused at work.

00:04:13.030 --> 00:04:16.358
The US military, both Marines
and soldiers in the army,

00:04:16.358 --> 00:04:17.899
are using mindfulness
and meditation,

00:04:17.899 --> 00:04:20.980
not to become better snipers,
but to become more resilient

00:04:20.980 --> 00:04:24.070
when they're back home and
also on the battlefield.

00:04:24.070 --> 00:04:27.550
And even the Seattle Seahawks--
this is Russell Wilson.

00:04:27.550 --> 00:04:30.160
He's playing in the
Super Bowl on Sunday.

00:04:30.160 --> 00:04:33.690
They've made mindfulness
a core part of training

00:04:33.690 --> 00:04:35.669
at the Seattle
Seahawks training camp.

00:04:35.669 --> 00:04:37.210
And some would say
that that's helped

00:04:37.210 --> 00:04:40.310
them appear in two
consecutive Super Bowls.

00:04:40.310 --> 00:04:43.210
At the World Economic Forum,
I was just in Davos last week,

00:04:43.210 --> 00:04:47.170
every day started with an hour
of mindfulness meditation led

00:04:47.170 --> 00:04:49.720
by Jon Kabat-Zinn, who's
one of the guys that really

00:04:49.720 --> 00:04:51.660
got this movement
going many years ago

00:04:51.660 --> 00:04:53.940
and has sustained it for
the last several decades.

00:04:53.940 --> 00:04:56.040
And I wrote a story
about it for the times--

00:04:56.040 --> 00:04:58.470
"Amid the Chattering of
the Global Elite, a Silent

00:04:58.470 --> 00:04:59.169
Interlude."

00:04:59.169 --> 00:05:00.960
There was a panel about
mindful leadership,

00:05:00.960 --> 00:05:03.540
and there was another one
later in the week about mindful

00:05:03.540 --> 00:05:05.870
neuroscience.

00:05:05.870 --> 00:05:08.160
Of all the things we wrote
about, from central bankers

00:05:08.160 --> 00:05:10.850
to oil prices, this
was the one that

00:05:10.850 --> 00:05:13.152
was the most read of
all our Davos coverage.

00:05:13.152 --> 00:05:15.110
And there's even a
magazine. "Mindful Magazine"

00:05:15.110 --> 00:05:16.880
is on the newsstands,
documenting

00:05:16.880 --> 00:05:19.730
this whole range of
professionals that

00:05:19.730 --> 00:05:21.570
are embracing mindfulness
for one reason

00:05:21.570 --> 00:05:24.600
or another-- doctors,
lawyers, policeman, and more.

00:05:24.600 --> 00:05:25.910
So what is mindfulness?

00:05:25.910 --> 00:05:28.270
For those who
haven't taken gPause,

00:05:28.270 --> 00:05:30.500
who haven't taken
Search Inside Yourself,

00:05:30.500 --> 00:05:32.800
it's paying attention
in the present moment,

00:05:32.800 --> 00:05:36.960
on purpose, in a particular
way, and nonjudgmentally.

00:05:36.960 --> 00:05:38.751
And I know that's a mouthful.

00:05:38.751 --> 00:05:40.250
But if you boil it
down, it's really

00:05:40.250 --> 00:05:43.170
about being right
here, right now.

00:05:43.170 --> 00:05:46.830
It's doing what we did for
just a minute earlier on.

00:05:46.830 --> 00:05:48.594
It's not letting
ourselves get caught up

00:05:48.594 --> 00:05:50.010
on the hamster
wheel of our minds,

00:05:50.010 --> 00:05:52.280
not letting ourselves
be always preoccupied

00:05:52.280 --> 00:05:54.930
about the future,
dwelling on the past.

00:05:54.930 --> 00:05:57.260
It's being right here
right now and noticing

00:05:57.260 --> 00:06:01.160
what's going on in our
thoughts, emotions, and bodies.

00:06:01.160 --> 00:06:03.180
Who coined this term?

00:06:03.180 --> 00:06:05.542
Jon Kabat-Zinn-- he's
a molecular biologist

00:06:05.542 --> 00:06:07.500
from the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology.

00:06:07.500 --> 00:06:09.340
So he's not just
hippie vagabond who

00:06:09.340 --> 00:06:13.060
came back and tried to
repurpose some ancient wisdom.

00:06:13.060 --> 00:06:15.590
He's a very serious guy, and
he's done more than anyone

00:06:15.590 --> 00:06:16.840
over the last several decades.

00:06:16.840 --> 00:06:18.880
He developed this thing called
mindfulness-based stress

00:06:18.880 --> 00:06:19.379
reduction.

00:06:19.379 --> 00:06:20.680
It's an eight week course.

00:06:20.680 --> 00:06:21.950
It's taught here in London.

00:06:21.950 --> 00:06:22.920
I highly recommend it.

00:06:22.920 --> 00:06:27.260
I've done it, and it really has
helped secularize mindfulness.

00:06:27.260 --> 00:06:29.250
It's made it so
accessible to people

00:06:29.250 --> 00:06:30.467
in all those professions.

00:06:30.467 --> 00:06:32.050
And I think I wouldn't
be on the stage

00:06:32.050 --> 00:06:33.990
if it wasn't for
the work he'd do.

00:06:33.990 --> 00:06:36.790
So how does Jon Kabat-Zinn
suggest we actually

00:06:36.790 --> 00:06:37.710
cultivate mindfulness?

00:06:37.710 --> 00:06:40.480
Well, meditation--
it's not the only way,

00:06:40.480 --> 00:06:46.340
but it's unfortunately the
main way-- and more meditation.

00:06:46.340 --> 00:06:48.200
And let's just think
back to what we did.

00:06:48.200 --> 00:06:50.250
It's sitting upright,
comfortably--

00:06:50.250 --> 00:06:53.180
it's what we just did-- finding
the sensation of your breath.

00:06:53.180 --> 00:06:55.330
And the whole game, this
is the whole thing, when

00:06:55.330 --> 00:06:57.910
your mind wanders, just
bring your attention

00:06:57.910 --> 00:06:59.940
back to the breath.

00:06:59.940 --> 00:07:03.270
Let's just do it one more time,
this time for only 30 seconds.

00:07:03.270 --> 00:07:07.836
Find a position that's upright,
dignified, comfortable.

00:07:07.836 --> 00:07:10.540
And when I ring the bell,
just focus on your breath.

00:07:10.540 --> 00:07:12.510
I won't interrupt this time.

00:07:12.510 --> 00:07:15.380
When the mind wanders,
back to the breath.

00:07:15.380 --> 00:07:17.766
[BELL RINGING]

00:07:38.514 --> 00:07:39.502
[BELL RINGING]

00:07:40.520 --> 00:07:47.009
OK, not so painful, I hope--
that was just 30 seconds.

00:07:47.009 --> 00:07:47.550
I don't know.

00:07:47.550 --> 00:07:51.210
How long do you guys
sit for at gPause, Don?

00:07:51.210 --> 00:07:54.350
20 minutes, OK,
that's 40 of those.

00:07:54.350 --> 00:07:55.420
I think we could do it.

00:07:55.420 --> 00:07:57.045
We're not going to
do it today, though.

00:07:57.045 --> 00:07:59.850
But sitting meditation can
be a lot for some people,

00:07:59.850 --> 00:08:01.000
so it's not the only way.

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:03.280
There's sitting meditation,
but there's also

00:08:03.280 --> 00:08:04.160
walking meditation.

00:08:04.160 --> 00:08:05.076
There's the body scan.

00:08:05.076 --> 00:08:07.087
And I'll talk about a
few other techniques

00:08:07.087 --> 00:08:09.420
over the course of this talk
that are ways just to pause

00:08:09.420 --> 00:08:12.020
and be mindful in the midst
of our busy work days.

00:08:12.020 --> 00:08:14.010
And what happens
when we actually

00:08:14.010 --> 00:08:16.200
start embodying
this mindfulness?

00:08:16.200 --> 00:08:17.660
Well, a common
way it's described

00:08:17.660 --> 00:08:19.840
is a move from
reaction to response.

00:08:19.840 --> 00:08:24.110
So something happens, and
typically we just automatically

00:08:24.110 --> 00:08:25.160
respond.

00:08:25.160 --> 00:08:26.212
We react.

00:08:26.212 --> 00:08:27.670
And oftentimes, we
don't even think

00:08:27.670 --> 00:08:30.320
about what it is we're going to
do, how we're going to respond,

00:08:30.320 --> 00:08:32.360
where we're going to come
from, the quality of presence

00:08:32.360 --> 00:08:34.080
we're going to bring
to that interaction.

00:08:34.080 --> 00:08:37.140
Mindfulness--
cultivating the ability

00:08:37.140 --> 00:08:39.710
to just pause for
these brief seconds--

00:08:39.710 --> 00:08:43.370
allows us to inject
mindfulness after that stimulus

00:08:43.370 --> 00:08:44.490
and respond.

00:08:44.490 --> 00:08:48.490
And often the result is more
equanimity, more harmonious

00:08:48.490 --> 00:08:49.320
interactions.

00:08:49.320 --> 00:08:52.720
It can be good, especially in
a busy, big place like Google.

00:08:52.720 --> 00:08:54.760
Mindfulness is an
innate human quality.

00:08:54.760 --> 00:08:56.080
This is nothing specific.

00:08:56.080 --> 00:08:58.460
This is nothing that
Jon Kabat-Zinn invented.

00:08:58.460 --> 00:09:01.730
You all just found mindfulness
right here, in Google,

00:09:01.730 --> 00:09:05.450
in London, for just a
minute, for just 30 seconds.

00:09:05.450 --> 00:09:08.190
It's something that we all
possess, and yet it is true,

00:09:08.190 --> 00:09:11.220
it is most closely associated
with the Buddhist tradition.

00:09:11.220 --> 00:09:14.380
The term mindfulness is
sprinkled across the Buddhist

00:09:14.380 --> 00:09:16.530
text like stars
across the night.

00:09:16.530 --> 00:09:19.740
And Buddhist meditation
is often aimed

00:09:19.740 --> 00:09:22.370
at actually cultivating
the quality of mindfulness.

00:09:22.370 --> 00:09:24.720
But today, thanks
largely to Jon Kabat-Zinn

00:09:24.720 --> 00:09:26.480
and some of his
colleagues, mindfulness

00:09:26.480 --> 00:09:28.200
is really a secular pursuit.

00:09:28.200 --> 00:09:30.930
It's been divorced
from that tradition.

00:09:30.930 --> 00:09:33.350
They've taken it out of
that religious context

00:09:33.350 --> 00:09:35.160
and really made it
accessible to everyone.

00:09:35.160 --> 00:09:37.670
And I think that's why
we're seeing Google, Goldman

00:09:37.670 --> 00:09:40.830
Sachs, General Mills,
and more embrace this.

00:09:40.830 --> 00:09:43.600
And also, a company
called Aetna.

00:09:43.600 --> 00:09:44.780
This is Mark Bertolini.

00:09:44.780 --> 00:09:46.310
He's the CEO of Aetna.

00:09:46.310 --> 00:09:49.750
It's a $40 billion, Fortune
100 company, big health care

00:09:49.750 --> 00:09:51.365
provider in the United States.

00:09:51.365 --> 00:09:54.340
And I'm just going to tell
you his story for a minute.

00:09:54.340 --> 00:09:56.020
Several years ago,
Mark almost died.

00:09:56.020 --> 00:09:59.120
He was in a skiing accident
with his family on vacation.

00:09:59.120 --> 00:10:00.780
He broke his collar bone.

00:10:00.780 --> 00:10:04.810
His shoulder was dislocated,
and he tore a ton of the nerves

00:10:04.810 --> 00:10:05.990
in his arm.

00:10:05.990 --> 00:10:10.980
And when he got back,
he could barely work.

00:10:10.980 --> 00:10:15.090
The pain was so severe
that he almost quit.

00:10:15.090 --> 00:10:17.620
He almost absolutely
didn't even return to work.

00:10:17.620 --> 00:10:18.544
He tried drugs.

00:10:18.544 --> 00:10:19.460
The drugs didn't work.

00:10:19.460 --> 00:10:20.930
He tried all of them.

00:10:20.930 --> 00:10:22.090
He tried physical therapy.

00:10:22.090 --> 00:10:24.760
Physical therapy didn't work,
and he was really suffering.

00:10:24.760 --> 00:10:27.205
He was considering ending his
career, and he was a real up

00:10:27.205 --> 00:10:29.660
and comer.

00:10:29.660 --> 00:10:32.440
Then finally someone
suggested, you try yoga.

00:10:32.440 --> 00:10:34.790
And he said, no way, no how.

00:10:34.790 --> 00:10:36.760
Yoga is for sissies, not for me.

00:10:36.760 --> 00:10:39.320
He was a very serious,
type A kind of guy.

00:10:39.320 --> 00:10:41.520
And they said,
just try it, Mark.

00:10:41.520 --> 00:10:43.310
So he went to his
first yoga class,

00:10:43.310 --> 00:10:45.980
and he did his Sun Salutations.

00:10:45.980 --> 00:10:47.590
And he got through it.

00:10:47.590 --> 00:10:49.820
And the next day, he
was so sore he almost

00:10:49.820 --> 00:10:51.010
wanted those drugs again.

00:10:51.010 --> 00:10:53.800
And he realized that not only
was yoga not for sissies,

00:10:53.800 --> 00:10:57.120
it was a very serious practice
that he ought to investigate.

00:10:57.120 --> 00:10:59.500
He became a devoted
yogi, and that

00:10:59.500 --> 00:11:01.350
led to an experience
of mindfulness.

00:11:01.350 --> 00:11:03.910
He started practicing
mindfulness meditation.

00:11:03.910 --> 00:11:05.260
Fast forward several months.

00:11:05.260 --> 00:11:07.430
He's off the drugs.

00:11:07.430 --> 00:11:08.911
He still feels pain, absolutely.

00:11:08.911 --> 00:11:10.660
But like the patients
I mentioned earlier,

00:11:10.660 --> 00:11:11.900
he's not suffering as much.

00:11:11.900 --> 00:11:14.070
He's able to manage his
pain more effectively.

00:11:14.070 --> 00:11:14.760
And he goes.

00:11:14.760 --> 00:11:15.926
He wasn't CEO at that point.

00:11:15.926 --> 00:11:19.520
He becomes CEO, and Aetna is
frankly doing better than ever.

00:11:19.520 --> 00:11:21.970
So then he says, well,
if it works for me,

00:11:21.970 --> 00:11:24.340
why don't we bring
it to our employees?

00:11:24.340 --> 00:11:26.690
So he goes to his chief
medical officer at Aetna

00:11:26.690 --> 00:11:30.970
and he says, I want to teach
mindfulness to Aetna employees.

00:11:30.970 --> 00:11:33.300
And Lonnie, this guy,
he says, you're crazy.

00:11:33.300 --> 00:11:35.080
Just because everyone
else is meditating,

00:11:35.080 --> 00:11:37.565
it doesn't mean your
employees have to as well.

00:11:37.565 --> 00:11:39.440
And he said, we're an
evidence-based company.

00:11:39.440 --> 00:11:41.656
Let's just try it.

