And Lonnie says, fine,
small pilot-- couple hundred

00:11:43.780 --> 00:11:45.014
employees on both coasts.

00:11:45.014 --> 00:11:46.430
Mark says, I'll
do you one better.

00:11:46.430 --> 00:11:49.230
Let's get Duke University
in to measure the results.

00:11:49.230 --> 00:11:51.340
So they start it-- small
pilot program, run it

00:11:51.340 --> 00:11:52.090
for a few months.

00:11:52.090 --> 00:11:53.090
What do they find?

00:11:53.090 --> 00:11:55.460
Those few hundred
employees-- a., they love it,

00:11:55.460 --> 00:11:58.060
say the quality of life,
their experience of work,

00:11:58.060 --> 00:11:58.780
has gone up.

00:11:58.780 --> 00:12:00.680
But not only that, they
seem to be healthier.

00:12:00.680 --> 00:12:02.060
They seem to be less stressed.

00:12:02.060 --> 00:12:05.210
They were reporting their
self-reported stress symptoms

00:12:05.210 --> 00:12:05.730
way down.

00:12:05.730 --> 00:12:07.780
Their engagement
with work, way up.

00:12:07.780 --> 00:12:10.160
So Lonnie, the chief medical
officer, he says, OK,

00:12:10.160 --> 00:12:11.530
let's expand it.

00:12:11.530 --> 00:12:13.270
They roll it out
then to thousands

00:12:13.270 --> 00:12:15.510
of Aetna employees
around the country.

00:12:18.140 --> 00:12:21.300
And, again, it's a hit.

00:12:21.300 --> 00:12:23.970
After a year of this,
they look at all the data.

00:12:23.970 --> 00:12:27.790
They look at all the results,
and it's made a difference.

00:12:27.790 --> 00:12:29.980
Not only are all the
self-reported scores

00:12:29.980 --> 00:12:32.480
off the charts-- people love
it, they're feeling better--

00:12:32.480 --> 00:12:34.990
but in fact, health
care costs at Aetna

00:12:34.990 --> 00:12:37.920
for that first full year
came down dramatically.

00:12:37.920 --> 00:12:41.130
They came down 9%, which
for Aetna was $7 million.

00:12:41.130 --> 00:12:42.409
And I asked Mark.

00:12:42.409 --> 00:12:44.450
I said, is that all
directly-- are you telling me

00:12:44.450 --> 00:12:45.910
meditation saved you $7 million?

00:12:45.910 --> 00:12:47.900
He said, I can't make
that direct corollary.

00:12:47.900 --> 00:12:49.500
I'm not going to overstep here.

00:12:49.500 --> 00:12:52.570
But he has to believe it made
a difference on the margins.

00:12:52.570 --> 00:12:54.077
If his employees
are less stressed,

00:12:54.077 --> 00:12:55.910
feeling better, going
to the infirmary less,

00:12:55.910 --> 00:12:58.080
taking fewer sick
days, maybe that's

00:12:58.080 --> 00:12:59.430
going to help the bottom line.

00:12:59.430 --> 00:12:59.950
So what did they do?

00:12:59.950 --> 00:13:00.825
They did mindfulness.

00:13:00.825 --> 00:13:02.960
They did yoga, but
they also rolled out

00:13:02.960 --> 00:13:04.530
other forms of
mindfulness training.

00:13:04.530 --> 00:13:07.650
And there's one I want to
mention as another tip.

00:13:07.650 --> 00:13:11.260
And it involves the sandwich--
actually just eating, eating

00:13:11.260 --> 00:13:12.750
anything.

00:13:12.750 --> 00:13:16.440
Aetna rolled out a program
called Metabolic Bytes.

00:13:16.440 --> 00:13:18.980
And he actually
got his employees

00:13:18.980 --> 00:13:20.580
to focus on what
they were eating,

00:13:20.580 --> 00:13:21.707
how much they were eating.

00:13:21.707 --> 00:13:23.790
And what did they do when
they started to do that?

00:13:23.790 --> 00:13:25.836
They started to eat less.

00:13:25.836 --> 00:13:27.710
And through this whole
program, they actually

00:13:27.710 --> 00:13:30.330
engaged a bunch of the
overweight and obese Aetna

00:13:30.330 --> 00:13:31.202
employees.

00:13:31.202 --> 00:13:33.410
And they were actually able
to help them lose weight,

00:13:33.410 --> 00:13:35.380
just through
mindfulness of eating.

00:13:35.380 --> 00:13:37.550
And it's bringing that
same quality of attention

00:13:37.550 --> 00:13:40.424
that we practiced
earlier to our attention.

00:13:40.424 --> 00:13:41.340
And what do we notice?

00:13:41.340 --> 00:13:43.549
So often we're just shovelling
food and maybe surfing

00:13:43.549 --> 00:13:45.714
our smartphone, looking at
the web at the same time,

00:13:45.714 --> 00:13:46.680
eating at our desk.

00:13:46.680 --> 00:13:49.450
When we stop doing
that, we can actually

00:13:49.450 --> 00:13:53.074
eat just what we need
instead of automatically

00:13:53.074 --> 00:13:54.490
finishing everything
on the table.

00:13:54.490 --> 00:13:55.860
And that was an
amazing, amazing thing

00:13:55.860 --> 00:13:57.193
that I've tried to take with me.

00:13:57.193 --> 00:14:00.111
I try to eat at my desk
less than I need to.

00:14:00.111 --> 00:14:02.360
But at "The New York Times"
it's not always an option.

00:14:02.360 --> 00:14:04.910
But when I actually
find the time,

00:14:04.910 --> 00:14:07.320
a good mindful meal can help.

00:14:07.320 --> 00:14:09.115
So Aetna brought it to
thousands of people.

00:14:09.115 --> 00:14:10.740
He saved millions in
health care costs,

00:14:10.740 --> 00:14:13.860
then he started offering it to
other companies as a service.

00:14:13.860 --> 00:14:17.430
So Aetna now offers yoga
and meditation classes

00:14:17.430 --> 00:14:19.320
to many of its employees.

00:14:19.320 --> 00:14:21.570
So if that all weren't enough,
I was totally impressed

00:14:21.570 --> 00:14:21.760
with Aetna.

00:14:21.760 --> 00:14:23.424
And then Mark, just
this month, did

00:14:23.424 --> 00:14:24.590
something really incredible.

00:14:24.590 --> 00:14:28.210
He came back from
Christmas vacation,

00:14:28.210 --> 00:14:31.400
and he had read this book--
"Capital in the Twenty-First

00:14:31.400 --> 00:14:32.830
Century" by Thomas Piketty.

00:14:32.830 --> 00:14:35.850
And he was so moved by
the stories of inequality

00:14:35.850 --> 00:14:38.950
and the data that showed that
big corporations, like the one

00:14:38.950 --> 00:14:41.680
he runs, and big CEOs, like
him-- he's paid millions

00:14:41.680 --> 00:14:44.070
of dollars a year--
were exacerbating this

00:14:44.070 --> 00:14:45.750
that he felt compelled
to do something.

00:14:45.750 --> 00:14:46.825
So he went to his board.

00:14:46.825 --> 00:14:49.820
He gave everyone in the
board a copy of this book.

00:14:49.820 --> 00:14:51.480
And then he made a
public announcement.

00:14:51.480 --> 00:14:53.230
Out of the blue he
said, all of our lowest

00:14:53.230 --> 00:14:55.807
paid workers are
getting a 33% raise

00:14:55.807 --> 00:14:57.640
because I have an
obligation to do something

00:14:57.640 --> 00:14:58.570
about this problem.

00:14:58.570 --> 00:15:01.050
And I saw Mark in Davos.

00:15:01.050 --> 00:15:03.430
And I said, Mark, did
your meditation practice,

00:15:03.430 --> 00:15:06.130
did your mindfulness, have
anything to do with this?

00:15:06.130 --> 00:15:07.713
And he said, I'm not
going to tell you

00:15:07.713 --> 00:15:10.420
just because I meditated
I made this decision.

00:15:10.420 --> 00:15:12.090
But meditation and
mindfulness have

00:15:12.090 --> 00:15:16.150
made me more attuned to
other people's emotions.

00:15:16.150 --> 00:15:18.020
I'm more compassionate.

00:15:18.020 --> 00:15:20.130
I'm more in touch with
the needs of others.

00:15:20.130 --> 00:15:21.620
And I recognize
the interdependence

00:15:21.620 --> 00:15:24.450
and the interconnectedness
of the work we do

00:15:24.450 --> 00:15:27.820
and the broader
function of society.

00:15:27.820 --> 00:15:32.460
And, ultimately, he made
this very radical decision.

00:15:32.460 --> 00:15:34.720
So why am I the guy up
here telling you this,

00:15:34.720 --> 00:15:35.640
you might wonder?

00:15:35.640 --> 00:15:37.640
I grew up here in
the San Francisco

00:15:37.640 --> 00:15:39.960
Bay, beautiful
Northern California.

00:15:39.960 --> 00:15:41.530
And I was a confused kid.

00:15:41.530 --> 00:15:42.996
I was a confused teenager.

00:15:42.996 --> 00:15:44.370
I was a confused
college student.

00:15:44.370 --> 00:15:48.140
I asked lots of questions
about the big things in life.

00:15:48.140 --> 00:15:50.570
And I found no answers
in psychedelics.

00:15:50.570 --> 00:15:52.500
I found no answers in books.

00:15:52.500 --> 00:15:54.581
I tried everywhere, but
I couldn't find them.

00:15:54.581 --> 00:15:56.830
Then finally one night, it's
my first year of college.

00:15:56.830 --> 00:15:58.810
I'm home visiting my mom.

00:15:58.810 --> 00:16:01.170
I open a book on the
bookshelf, and it's

00:16:01.170 --> 00:16:04.094
an introduction to basic
Buddhist meditation.

00:16:04.094 --> 00:16:06.510
And for the first time, I read
something that makes sense.

00:16:06.510 --> 00:16:09.390
It says getting off the hamster
wheel of our mind is possible.

00:16:09.390 --> 00:16:11.590
Stopping obsessing about
the future and the past

00:16:11.590 --> 00:16:12.746
is actually attainable.

00:16:12.746 --> 00:16:14.120
And there's an
easy way to do it,

00:16:14.120 --> 00:16:16.960
and it's called
mindfulness and meditation.

00:16:16.960 --> 00:16:18.850
So I did what anyone would do.

00:16:18.850 --> 00:16:21.690
I got on a plane and went
as far away from my parents

00:16:21.690 --> 00:16:24.220
as I could to India.

00:16:24.220 --> 00:16:27.360
And I moved to Bodh Gaya, which
is a small, impoverished town

00:16:27.360 --> 00:16:29.290
in Northern India.

00:16:29.290 --> 00:16:31.890
And it's where the Buddha, they
say, was actually enlightened.

00:16:31.890 --> 00:16:33.710
I moved into a
Burmese monastery,

00:16:33.710 --> 00:16:36.180
where saffron-robed monks
woke me up every morning.

00:16:36.180 --> 00:16:38.470
There were peacocks
roaming the courtyard,

00:16:38.470 --> 00:16:40.469
and I studied with
different meditation masters

00:16:40.469 --> 00:16:41.260
for several months.

00:16:41.260 --> 00:16:42.950
I studied with Zen masters.

00:16:42.950 --> 00:16:46.300
I studied with supposedly
reincarnated Tibetan rinpoches,

00:16:46.300 --> 00:16:48.500
and I studied with
this guy, Munindraji.

00:16:48.500 --> 00:16:52.190
Anagarika Munindraji was
one of the most influential

00:16:52.190 --> 00:16:54.320
mindfulness teachers
of the 20th century.

00:16:54.320 --> 00:16:57.100
The students he taught
are still so responsible

00:16:57.100 --> 00:16:59.140
for the proliferation
of mindfulness

00:16:59.140 --> 00:17:00.310
that we're seeing today.

00:17:00.310 --> 00:17:02.601
And I was really fortunate
to spend quite a lot of time

00:17:02.601 --> 00:17:04.589
with him in the last
years of his life.

00:17:04.589 --> 00:17:08.210
And he emphasized more than
anything else, more than all

00:17:08.210 --> 00:17:09.710
the different
meditation techniques,

00:17:09.710 --> 00:17:11.839
he said something that
just resonated with me.

00:17:11.839 --> 00:17:15.990
He said, moment to moment,
everything you do, be mindful.

00:17:15.990 --> 00:17:17.550
If you're walking, be mindful.

00:17:17.550 --> 00:17:19.359
If you're eating be mindful.

00:17:19.359 --> 00:17:21.190
If you're just sitting
there, be mindful.

00:17:21.190 --> 00:17:24.220
Don't let your
mind just race off.

00:17:24.220 --> 00:17:26.730
Just actually practice
being here now.

00:17:26.730 --> 00:17:29.370
So there I am, sitting with
Munindraji under the Bodhi

00:17:29.370 --> 00:17:30.370
tree.

00:17:30.370 --> 00:17:31.750
I was younger then.

00:17:31.750 --> 00:17:36.130
There I am with another Tibetan
teacher, under the Bodhi tree

00:17:36.130 --> 00:17:36.760
again.

00:17:36.760 --> 00:17:39.852
And if I had stayed in India,
as I was tempted to do--

00:17:39.852 --> 00:17:42.310
I called my mom and I threatened
I was going to stay there,

00:17:42.310 --> 00:17:44.656
and she freaked out.

00:17:44.656 --> 00:17:46.030
If I had stayed
in India, I think

00:17:46.030 --> 00:17:47.990
I would look like this guy.

00:17:47.990 --> 00:17:52.200
That's Yogi Mike, and he's been
in India for a very long time.

00:17:52.200 --> 00:17:53.560
I didn't stay in India, though.

00:17:53.560 --> 00:17:54.610
I came back.

00:17:54.610 --> 00:17:56.565
I became a business journalist.

00:17:56.565 --> 00:17:58.460
I'm currently with
"The New York Times."

00:17:58.460 --> 00:18:00.960
Before that, I was with "The
Financial Times" for five years

00:18:00.960 --> 00:18:05.060
here in London, covering
media, marketing acquisitions.

00:18:05.060 --> 00:18:06.410
And I continue to meditate.

00:18:06.410 --> 00:18:10.070
I go to places like this,
Spirit Rock, north of Northern

00:18:10.070 --> 00:18:13.250
California, just
above San Francisco.

00:18:13.250 --> 00:18:15.050
But for the most
part, this has been

00:18:15.050 --> 00:18:18.440
my temple-- the
newsroom of newspapers,

00:18:18.440 --> 00:18:20.779
full of screaming
editors, fast deadlines.

00:18:20.779 --> 00:18:22.570
And I can assure you
after much experience,

00:18:22.570 --> 00:18:26.340
it's about the least
mindful place I can imagine.

00:18:26.340 --> 00:18:29.450
But it's where I earn my keep.

00:18:29.450 --> 00:18:31.870
It was while I was at the
FT that I wrote a magazine

00:18:31.870 --> 00:18:34.120
article that actually led
me to this stage right here.

00:18:34.120 --> 00:18:35.960
It was called "The
Mind Business."

00:18:35.960 --> 00:18:37.600
It was published in 2012.

00:18:37.600 --> 00:18:40.380
And I wrote it when I was
kind of at an impasse.

00:18:40.380 --> 00:18:42.130
I had done a bunch
of big stories.

00:18:42.130 --> 00:18:44.170
I had interviewed
Bernie Madoff in prison.

00:18:44.170 --> 00:18:47.260
I had profiled
Zuckerberg in 2011,

00:18:47.260 --> 00:18:49.780
right as the company was
gearing up for that big push

00:18:49.780 --> 00:18:51.181
to go public.

00:18:51.181 --> 00:18:52.180
But I was at an impasse.

00:18:52.180 --> 00:18:53.971
I didn't have a big
story I was working on,

00:18:53.971 --> 00:18:56.900
which for a journalist is about
the most frustrating thing.

00:18:56.900 --> 00:18:59.590
And then I heard about this
company, General Mills.

00:18:59.590 --> 00:19:01.560
I heard General
Mills in Minneapolis,

00:19:01.560 --> 00:19:05.607
Minnesota was actually teaching
their employees to meditate.

00:19:05.607 --> 00:19:06.690
And a light bulb went off.

00:19:06.690 --> 00:19:07.939
I said, I have to figure this.

00:19:07.939 --> 00:19:09.890
This is finally the
moment where I can join up

00:19:09.890 --> 00:19:11.431
these two disparate
parts of my life.

00:19:11.431 --> 00:19:14.340
So I got on a plane,
flew out there,

00:19:14.340 --> 00:19:16.460
eager to see what the
makers of Haagen-Dazs ice

00:19:16.460 --> 00:19:19.270
cream and Cheerios had to
tell me about meditation.

00:19:19.270 --> 00:19:22.660
And when I got there,
this is what I found.

00:19:22.660 --> 00:19:26.250
It looked so similar to
actually the very things

00:19:26.250 --> 00:19:27.800
we had been doing in India.

00:19:27.800 --> 00:19:29.430
I walked into this
conference room.

00:19:29.430 --> 00:19:32.330
It was 3 o'clock on
a Tuesday, and people

00:19:32.330 --> 00:19:34.450
were meditating
in total silence.

00:19:34.450 --> 00:19:36.660
And not only that, but the
phrases they were using,

00:19:36.660 --> 00:19:40.710
the very words, were echoes
of what I had heard in India.

00:19:40.710 --> 00:19:45.970
And the woman who was leading
all this was Janice Marturano.

00:19:45.970 --> 00:19:48.330
Janice had a story
not unlike Mark's.

00:19:48.330 --> 00:19:49.640
She had hit rock bottom.

00:19:49.640 --> 00:19:52.230
She was the deputy general
counsel at General Mills.

00:19:52.230 --> 00:19:54.880
And for a year, she worked to
push through the $10 billion

00:19:54.880 --> 00:19:58.190
merger of Pillsbury
and General Mills.

00:19:58.190 --> 00:19:59.580
It was absolutely draining.

00:19:59.580 --> 00:20:02.100
She had to fight the
SEC, fight the FTC.

00:20:02.100 --> 00:20:02.880
It was grueling.

00:20:02.880 --> 00:20:06.020
And in the midst of
this professional toil,

00:20:06.020 --> 00:20:08.182
both of her parents
died, a personal blow

00:20:08.182 --> 00:20:09.390
that absolutely levelled her.

00:20:09.390 --> 00:20:11.110
She finally got the
deal passed, but when

00:20:11.110 --> 00:20:12.330
she got back to
work she was spent.

00:20:12.330 --> 00:20:13.740
She had nothing
left in the tank.

00:20:13.740 --> 00:20:15.620
She was emotionally,
intellectually

00:20:15.620 --> 00:20:18.920
just depleted-- felt like
she almost couldn't go on.

00:20:18.920 --> 00:20:20.600
A friend suggested
she try meditation.

00:20:20.600 --> 00:20:23.430
She said, no way, no
how, not new age for me.

00:20:23.430 --> 00:20:26.530
I'm a solid Midwestern
girl, not going to happen.

00:20:26.530 --> 00:20:28.910
Finally, she circled
back a few weeks later,

00:20:28.910 --> 00:20:30.740
said, tell me a bit
more about that.

00:20:30.740 --> 00:20:32.200
Soon she was on a
plane to Arizona,

00:20:32.200 --> 00:20:33.783
where she studied
with Jon Kabat-Zinn,

00:20:33.783 --> 00:20:37.390
the molecular
biologist from MIT.

00:20:37.390 --> 00:20:40.460
After a day with
Jon Kabat-Zinn, she

00:20:40.460 --> 00:20:43.360
was ready to get back on
the plane to Minneapolis.

00:20:43.360 --> 00:20:45.650
After five days, she
didn't want to leave.

00:20:45.650 --> 00:20:48.230
It took a while, but
meditation started

00:20:48.230 --> 00:20:50.606
to change the way
she saw herself

00:20:50.606 --> 00:20:51.980
and the way she
was able to work.

00:20:51.980 --> 00:20:55.370
She got back to Minneapolis, and
people noticed she had changed.

00:20:55.370 --> 00:20:57.510
There was a bounce
back in her step.

00:20:57.510 --> 00:21:00.050
In very stressful meetings,
she was able to keep her cool,

00:21:00.050 --> 00:21:02.140
even as people around
her were blowing up.

00:21:02.140 --> 00:21:04.940
And finally people started
asking her, what's changed?

00:21:04.940 --> 00:21:05.440
Are you OK?

00:21:05.440 --> 00:21:06.640
What's different?

00:21:06.640 --> 00:21:07.490
And she started telling
them, well, I've

00:21:07.490 --> 00:21:08.580
been practicing meditation.

00:21:08.580 --> 00:21:09.460
I've been practicing
mindfulness.

00:21:09.460 --> 00:21:11.000
If you're interested,
let me know.

00:21:11.000 --> 00:21:12.860
Before long she had a quorum.

00:21:12.860 --> 00:21:14.450
She had a dozen
people, and so she

00:21:14.450 --> 00:21:16.890
started sitting-- much as
sitting groups have started

00:21:16.890 --> 00:21:20.490
in companies all around
the globe right now.

00:21:20.490 --> 00:21:23.590
And soon, that 12
turned into 20.

00:21:23.590 --> 00:21:24.970
20 turned into 100.

00:21:24.970 --> 00:21:26.410
General Mills heard about this.

00:21:26.410 --> 00:21:28.710
The higher ups, they said,
OK, let's sanction it.

00:21:28.710 --> 00:21:30.050
Let's build a program around it.

00:21:30.050 --> 00:21:31.759
They gave her the
autonomy and the budget

00:21:31.759 --> 00:21:33.341
to start a mindful
leadership program.

00:21:33.341 --> 00:21:34.710
They started doing the research.

00:21:34.710 --> 00:21:36.610
And now, there's
a meditation room

00:21:36.610 --> 00:21:39.410
in every building on General
Mills' corporate campus.

00:21:39.410 --> 00:21:41.960
It's just an extraordinary
testament to their commitment

00:21:41.960 --> 00:21:42.820
to this.

00:21:42.820 --> 00:21:44.930
And Janice, she teaches
sitting meditation.

00:21:44.930 --> 00:21:47.180
She teaches walking meditation,
which we unfortunately

00:21:47.180 --> 00:21:48.440
don't have time for today.

00:21:48.440 --> 00:21:51.010
But she also talks about
the purposeful pause.

00:21:51.010 --> 00:21:55.780
And that's that interjection
of mindfulness between stimulus

00:21:55.780 --> 00:21:57.330
and our response
or our reaction.

00:21:57.330 --> 00:21:59.621
Previously, she would just
grab the phone when it rang.

00:21:59.621 --> 00:22:01.280
It's certainly what
I am trained to do.

00:22:01.280 --> 00:22:02.750
As a mergers and
acquisitions reporter,

00:22:02.750 --> 00:22:04.583
it could always be a
source giving me a tip.

00:22:04.583 --> 00:22:06.100
And I have to stop myself.

00:22:06.100 --> 00:22:09.210
So what I try to do is
when the phone rings,

00:22:09.210 --> 00:22:11.955
I just let it ring
once, maybe even twice.

00:22:11.955 --> 00:22:12.580
And guess what?

00:22:12.580 --> 00:22:14.163
The people are still
on the other line

00:22:14.163 --> 00:22:15.360
waiting to talk to me.

00:22:15.360 --> 00:22:18.750
But just interjecting that brief
pause to check in with myself,

00:22:18.750 --> 00:22:21.100
to check in with how
my body is feeling,

00:22:21.100 --> 00:22:25.220
it allows me to come from
a place of equanimity

00:22:25.220 --> 00:22:26.676
when I pick up that phone.

00:22:26.676 --> 00:22:28.550
And it's amazing how
much can be accomplished

00:22:28.550 --> 00:22:30.580
with even a few seconds.

00:22:30.580 --> 00:22:32.760
Here, more General
Mills employees

00:22:32.760 --> 00:22:34.735
trying a different kind
of purposeful pause.

00:22:38.530 --> 00:22:41.450
Now, the mind business
went viral, in as much

00:22:41.450 --> 00:22:44.770
as an article for the
Financial Times can.

00:22:44.770 --> 00:22:47.750
People wanted to know
who else was doing this,

00:22:47.750 --> 00:22:50.680
where could they find
it, what was the data.

00:22:50.680 --> 00:22:52.530
And I didn't have
any of those answers.

00:22:52.530 --> 00:22:55.160
It was more than two
years ago at this point.

00:22:55.160 --> 00:22:58.700
I wanted to know more, and
so I set out on this journey

00:22:58.700 --> 00:23:01.940
into the contemplative
heart of the business world.

00:23:01.940 --> 00:23:05.650
I found all these companies and
more are practicing mindfulness

00:23:05.650 --> 00:23:07.830
and meditation in
one way or another.

00:23:07.830 --> 00:23:10.100
And it's really picking up
steam-- small businesses,

00:23:10.100 --> 00:23:13.037
large businesses, and
companies like Green Mountain.

00:23:13.037 --> 00:23:14.620
Green Mountain
Coffee-- I think you're

00:23:14.620 --> 00:23:18.700
spared their K-Cups here, but
many businesses across the US

00:23:18.700 --> 00:23:20.230
are subjected to them.

00:23:20.230 --> 00:23:23.150
They make prepackaged coffee.

00:23:23.150 --> 00:23:25.370
And the CEO, Bob
Stiller, that's him

00:23:25.370 --> 00:23:28.310
as pictured in "Fortune
Magazine" some years ago.

00:23:28.310 --> 00:23:32.150
He, unlike maybe Mark
Bertolini and Janice Marturano,

00:23:32.150 --> 00:23:33.850
he was kind of a hippy.

00:23:33.850 --> 00:23:35.760
He traveled through Asia.

00:23:35.760 --> 00:23:37.607
Before he took
over Green Mountain

00:23:37.607 --> 00:23:39.440
and made it a
multi-billion-dollar business,

00:23:39.440 --> 00:23:42.510
he started EZ Wider
Rolling Paper Company.

00:23:42.510 --> 00:23:46.790
So you get the sense of
the kind of guy he was.

00:23:46.790 --> 00:23:49.186
But at a certain point, he
said, heck, I'm a billionaire.

00:23:49.186 --> 00:23:50.310
I've made this big company.

00:23:50.310 --> 00:23:52.830
I'm going to do want,
started teaching mindfulness

00:23:52.830 --> 00:23:55.430
to his inner sanctum
of employees, his just

00:23:55.430 --> 00:23:56.660
core executive team.

00:23:56.660 --> 00:23:58.460
They loved it, same story.

00:23:58.460 --> 00:24:00.330
They rolled it out
to more employees,

00:24:00.330 --> 00:24:02.200
to middle management--
to graphic designers,

00:24:02.200 --> 00:24:05.210
to supply chain managers in the
corporate office in Vermont.

00:24:05.210 --> 00:24:06.189
Everyone loved it.

00:24:06.189 --> 00:24:08.480
And then, finally, they did
something really wonderful,

00:24:08.480 --> 00:24:08.980
I think.

00:24:08.980 --> 00:24:11.810
They said, this is great,
but we have tens of thousands

00:24:11.810 --> 00:24:14.760
of employees in factories
around the country.

00:24:14.760 --> 00:24:18.200
These are the guys on the
floor, driving trucks,

00:24:18.200 --> 00:24:19.954
who every day work
12 hour shifts

00:24:19.954 --> 00:24:22.120
putting our coffee in boxes,
getting them on trucks,

00:24:22.120 --> 00:24:23.150
and delivering it.

00:24:23.150 --> 00:24:25.040
They're probably more
stressed than we are.

00:24:25.040 --> 00:24:25.873
And they were right.

00:24:25.873 --> 00:24:28.160
So they started working
with a yoga teacher,

00:24:28.160 --> 00:24:31.060
and they developed mindful
yoga, mindful stretching,

00:24:31.060 --> 00:24:35.640
that now Green Mountain
employees do before they start

00:24:35.640 --> 00:24:38.060
every shift, just 10
minutes of mindful

00:24:38.060 --> 00:24:40.900
stretching in the locker rooms
as they're getting ready.

00:24:40.900 --> 00:24:43.310
And the locker room, the
environment in the locker room,

00:24:43.310 --> 00:24:44.530
has actually changed.

00:24:44.530 --> 00:24:46.220
It's quite extraordinary.

00:24:46.220 --> 00:24:48.700
And this is another
tip I want to suggest.

00:24:48.700 --> 00:24:51.930
Some people-- for Green
Mountain employees on the floor,

00:24:51.930 --> 00:24:53.450
it's their locker room.

00:24:53.450 --> 00:24:55.250
They just find a
mindfulness zone,

00:24:55.250 --> 00:24:57.880
somewhere in the
building, in the office,

00:24:57.880 --> 00:25:00.340
where it's your
cue to just pause,

00:25:00.340 --> 00:25:03.590
to put away your smartphone, to
stop the incessant chattering

00:25:03.590 --> 00:25:05.351
of the mind and
actually just check in.

00:25:05.351 --> 00:25:07.350
And you can practice the
same kind of meditation

00:25:07.350 --> 00:25:09.560
we did even if you're
just standing up.

00:25:09.560 --> 00:25:11.019
For me, it sometimes
the elevator.

00:25:11.019 --> 00:25:13.560
When I take the elevator up to
the cafeteria in "The New York

00:25:13.560 --> 00:25:16.470
Times" building, I just
try to put my phone away.

00:25:16.470 --> 00:25:18.410
And it's just 30 seconds or so.

00:25:18.410 --> 00:25:21.580
But when I get off that
elevator, I'm somewhat renewed.

00:25:21.580 --> 00:25:22.360
I'm refreshed.

00:25:22.360 --> 00:25:24.490
It's a purposeful
pause that's allowed

00:25:24.490 --> 00:25:28.640
me to just recenter
myself and carry on.

00:25:28.640 --> 00:25:29.960
So what is all this doing?

00:25:29.960 --> 00:25:32.907
Well, one thing is it's
making us less stressed.

00:25:32.907 --> 00:25:35.240
Mindfulness, it's been proven
through study after study,

00:25:35.240 --> 00:25:36.840
can actually reduce
our stress levels.

00:25:36.840 --> 00:25:38.550
We've heard it from the
different companies,

00:25:38.550 --> 00:25:40.860
but there's a lot of academic
and scientific research

00:25:40.860 --> 00:25:41.882
that proves as much.

00:25:41.882 --> 00:25:44.090
It's one of the reasons that
Jon Kabat-Zinn zeroed in

00:25:44.090 --> 00:25:46.120
on mindfulness-based
stress reduction.

00:25:46.120 --> 00:25:48.460
Mindfulness is a universal
sort of suffering.

00:25:48.460 --> 00:25:49.960
It's something we
all can relate to.

00:25:49.960 --> 00:25:52.140
We'd all love to be
less stressed, right?

00:25:52.140 --> 00:25:55.160
And so he didn't say that
mindfulness is about making us,

00:25:55.160 --> 00:25:56.900
you know, enlightened
or anything.

00:25:56.900 --> 00:25:59.560
He said, just make us
a little less stressed.

00:25:59.560 --> 00:26:01.326
That would be a
good thing, indeed.

00:26:01.326 --> 00:26:02.700
And the World
Health Organization

00:26:02.700 --> 00:26:06.617
estimates that stress costs
businesses $300 billion a year.

00:26:06.617 --> 00:26:09.200
Now, that's, like, one of those
abstract numbers from studies.

00:26:09.200 --> 00:26:12.450
I don't actually know what it
means, but I take the point.

00:26:12.450 --> 00:26:15.050
If we're all a
little less stressed,

00:26:15.050 --> 00:26:18.350
I got to believe that businesses
would be a bit more functional,

00:26:18.350 --> 00:26:20.700
maybe even a bit
more profitable.

00:26:20.700 --> 00:26:23.550
Mindfulness also seems
to improve our focus.

00:26:23.550 --> 00:26:26.190
Just think about the exercise
we did, bringing our attention

00:26:26.190 --> 00:26:28.060
back to the breath
over and over.

00:26:28.060 --> 00:26:31.130
Just as going to the gym
builds the muscles in our arms,

00:26:31.130 --> 00:26:35.430
so, too, mindfulness can build
up those attentional muscles,

00:26:35.430 --> 00:26:39.110
our capacity to sustain our
focus, to stay concentrated.

00:26:39.110 --> 00:26:43.030
And there's a great study that
shows that meditation actually

00:26:43.030 --> 00:26:45.000
reduces task switching.

00:26:45.000 --> 00:26:49.120
So that is they gave office
workers a series of tasks,

00:26:49.120 --> 00:26:51.800
then they measured
how they did them.

00:26:51.800 --> 00:26:54.550
And no surprise, they were
kind of balking back and forth.

00:26:54.550 --> 00:26:55.800
They did email for 30 minutes.

00:26:55.800 --> 00:26:56.700
They did a little PowerPoint.

00:26:56.700 --> 00:26:58.130
They balked to their calendar.

00:26:58.130 --> 00:26:59.550
They wrote a report.

00:26:59.550 --> 00:27:00.850
They made an itinerary.

00:27:00.850 --> 00:27:02.970
Then they trained them
all in mindfulness,

00:27:02.970 --> 00:27:04.576
waited awhile, and
tried it again.

00:27:04.576 --> 00:27:05.450
And what did they do?

00:27:05.450 --> 00:27:09.380
The office workers, this
time, stayed on task

00:27:09.380 --> 00:27:11.100
for almost double
the amount of time.

00:27:11.100 --> 00:27:12.444
So they weren't super employees.

00:27:12.444 --> 00:27:14.360
They didn't get everything
done twice as fast,

00:27:14.360 --> 00:27:17.130
but they were actually
able to sustain their focus

00:27:17.130 --> 00:27:19.230
on basic tasks in
the office and not

00:27:19.230 --> 00:27:22.530
have this perpetual constant
ADD from which so many of us

00:27:22.530 --> 00:27:23.660
suffer.

00:27:23.660 --> 00:27:25.790
This focus, this kind
of being in the zone,

00:27:25.790 --> 00:27:27.960
is, I think, why
a lot of athletes

00:27:27.960 --> 00:27:31.689
are finding meditation to
be so effective as well.

00:27:31.689 --> 00:27:33.230
This is Russell
Okung, also appearing

00:27:33.230 --> 00:27:34.659
in the Super Bowl on Sunday.

00:27:34.659 --> 00:27:35.950
You'd think I'm a Seahawks fan.

00:27:35.950 --> 00:27:39.270
I'm actually a Patriots
fan, but the Seahwaks

00:27:39.270 --> 00:27:40.720
have really embraced this.

00:27:40.720 --> 00:27:42.560
And he talks about
meditation as being

00:27:42.560 --> 00:27:44.220
just as important
as lifting weights.

00:27:44.220 --> 00:27:45.630
It's about quieting your mind.

00:27:45.630 --> 00:27:48.990
And from a 6 foot 6, 300
pound guy with a $48 million

00:27:48.990 --> 00:27:52.040
contract, I'm not going
to argue with him.

00:27:52.040 --> 00:27:55.550
Also this focus is one of
the reasons why meditation

00:27:55.550 --> 00:27:57.260
seems to improve test scores.

00:27:57.260 --> 00:28:00.680
They've done a series
of tests and studies

00:28:00.680 --> 00:28:03.990
that show that compared to
control groups that haven't had

00:28:03.990 --> 00:28:06.370
mindfulness training,
the students that

00:28:06.370 --> 00:28:09.420
have had mindfulness training
seem to perform better

00:28:09.420 --> 00:28:11.550
on standardized test
scores in the US.

00:28:11.550 --> 00:28:14.196
This is a good time to mention
that this isn't all just coming

00:28:14.196 --> 00:28:14.820
out of nowhere.

00:28:14.820 --> 00:28:17.630
For the last several
decades, neuroscientists

00:28:17.630 --> 00:28:20.220
have been studying the
minds of meditators,

00:28:20.220 --> 00:28:24.010
trying to understand what's
going on in their heads.

00:28:24.010 --> 00:28:26.610
And this study of
meditation has coincided

00:28:26.610 --> 00:28:29.630
with a shift in the
world of neuroscience

00:28:29.630 --> 00:28:31.460
where they actually
have re-thought

00:28:31.460 --> 00:28:34.110
about the way we
understand our brains.

00:28:34.110 --> 00:28:36.290
For a long time, much
of the 20th century,

00:28:36.290 --> 00:28:39.090
it was assumed that the
brain kind of matured,

00:28:39.090 --> 00:28:41.740
it degraded, and that was it.

00:28:41.740 --> 00:28:43.756
Now we know that
there's actually

00:28:43.756 --> 00:28:45.130
something called
neuroplasticity.

00:28:45.130 --> 00:28:48.360
Our brains respond to whatever
stimulus we put in them.

00:28:48.360 --> 00:28:51.780
That's why in the
brains of violinists

00:28:51.780 --> 00:28:54.020
the part of the brain
responsible for acute motor

00:28:54.020 --> 00:28:57.450
function is much more highly
developed than in my brain,

00:28:57.450 --> 00:28:59.010
for example.

00:28:59.010 --> 00:29:02.260
And in the minds of meditators,
certain areas of the brain

00:29:02.260 --> 00:29:05.834
also appear to
become more robust.

00:29:05.834 --> 00:29:07.750
The prefrontal cortex,
which is evolutionarily

00:29:07.750 --> 00:29:12.090
the newest part of our brain, it
actually shows more gray matter

00:29:12.090 --> 00:29:14.870
in the brains of
mindfulness meditators.

00:29:14.870 --> 00:29:17.500
This is the part of the brain
responsible for higher order

00:29:17.500 --> 00:29:20.590
processing, our reason,
our executive functioning.

00:29:20.590 --> 00:29:23.710
And then the amygdala, which is
a little seahorse shaped region

00:29:23.710 --> 00:29:26.710
in the center of our brain that
releases stress hormones when

00:29:26.710 --> 00:29:29.090
we get anxious, when we
have that fight or flight

00:29:29.090 --> 00:29:33.130
reaction-- in the minds of
meditators, it's less reactive.

00:29:33.130 --> 00:29:36.430
It releases fewer hormones
when we do have a stimulus.

00:29:36.430 --> 00:29:40.140
And again, there's that pause
between stimulus and response.

00:29:40.140 --> 00:29:43.680
Mindfulness seems to give us
a bit more room right there.

00:29:43.680 --> 00:29:48.739
So here's scans of the minds
of a non-meditator on the left.

00:29:48.739 --> 00:29:49.530
This is your brain.

00:29:49.530 --> 00:29:50.905
This is your brain
on meditation.

00:29:50.905 --> 00:29:53.070
That's more gray matter
in the prefrontal cortex.

00:29:53.070 --> 00:29:56.080
I also had my brain scanned at
Yale by a great neuroscientist

00:29:56.080 --> 00:30:00.692
named Jud Brewer, and
this is what they found.

00:30:00.692 --> 00:30:03.150
And mindfulness, of course,
doesn't just change our brains.

00:30:03.150 --> 00:30:04.400
It changes our bodies, too.

00:30:04.400 --> 00:30:06.820
We heard it from others earlier.

00:30:06.820 --> 00:30:08.660
It can help the immune system.

00:30:08.660 --> 00:30:10.810
There's an amazing study
that Jon Kabat-Zinn did.

00:30:10.810 --> 00:30:13.393
It was one of the seminal ones
that really put him on the map.

00:30:13.393 --> 00:30:19.580
He gave the flu vaccine
to a large group.

00:30:19.580 --> 00:30:22.840
Then they gave them mindfulness
meditation to half the group.

00:30:22.840 --> 00:30:24.640
And compared to
the control group,

00:30:24.640 --> 00:30:27.920
those with the
mindfulness meditation,

00:30:27.920 --> 00:30:31.020
their immune systems responded
so much more strongly.

00:30:31.020 --> 00:30:34.520
And another amazing study
about patients with psoriasis,

00:30:34.520 --> 00:30:38.680
the skin defect--
they gave mindfulness

00:30:38.680 --> 00:30:41.840
meditation to
psoriasis patients who

00:30:41.840 --> 00:30:43.700
were getting standard
light box treatment.

00:30:43.700 --> 00:30:46.520
This is where they put them
in a kind of UV light box.

00:30:46.520 --> 00:30:48.710
It helps with the
skin irritation.

00:30:48.710 --> 00:30:51.940
And the patients that had
mindfulness meditation

00:30:51.940 --> 00:30:56.320
at the same time as the UV
responded and healed much,

00:30:56.320 --> 00:30:59.750
much faster than those who
were only getting the light box

00:30:59.750 --> 00:31:01.420
therapy.

00:31:01.420 --> 00:31:04.220
So less stressed, more
focused, maybe even

00:31:04.220 --> 00:31:07.520
healthier-- what about
more compassionate,

00:31:07.520 --> 00:31:09.230
maybe even kinder, too?

00:31:09.230 --> 00:31:12.160
That's the message from
this guy, Tim Ryan.

00:31:12.160 --> 00:31:14.680
He's a congressman
on Capitol Hill, part

00:31:14.680 --> 00:31:18.070
of the House of
Representatives, which

00:31:18.070 --> 00:31:21.140
is about the least
mindful place in America

00:31:21.140 --> 00:31:24.600
after "The New York
Times" newsroom.

00:31:24.600 --> 00:31:27.280
And he, for a long time,
was not a meditator.

00:31:27.280 --> 00:31:30.760
He's a 6 foot 4
college quarterback

00:31:30.760 --> 00:31:34.506
from Ohio, red-blooded
Catholic guy.

00:31:34.506 --> 00:31:35.880
After his second
term, though, he

00:31:35.880 --> 00:31:38.380
was preparing to get sworn
in for his third term,

00:31:38.380 --> 00:31:41.980
and the bickering, the
partisan fighting in Congress,

00:31:41.980 --> 00:31:43.447
was just too much for him.

00:31:43.447 --> 00:31:44.280
He needed something.

00:31:44.280 --> 00:31:45.530
He heard about Jon Kabat-Zinn.

00:31:45.530 --> 00:31:48.840
He went on a short retreat
with Jon Kabat-Zinn,

00:31:48.840 --> 00:31:49.970
and he came back renewed.

00:31:49.970 --> 00:31:51.120
He said, this is it.

00:31:51.120 --> 00:31:53.520
He wrote a book called
"A Mindful Nation."

00:31:53.520 --> 00:31:56.520
He's become the most
unlikely meditation advocate

00:31:56.520 --> 00:31:57.280
in the country.

00:31:57.280 --> 00:31:58.860
He has quiet time caucus.

00:31:58.860 --> 00:32:01.350
They meditate before
sessions on Capitol Hill.

00:32:01.350 --> 00:32:03.220
There he is in his office.

00:32:03.220 --> 00:32:05.890
And he is just doing
amazing things,

00:32:05.890 --> 00:32:08.390
even if the rest of
Congress can't get onboard.

00:32:08.390 --> 00:32:10.930
But I said, Tim, what has
actually been the difference?

00:32:10.930 --> 00:32:13.590
I mean, how has it changed
the way you do your job?

00:32:13.590 --> 00:32:17.130
And he said so often
before his calculations,

00:32:17.130 --> 00:32:18.630
the bills he was
going to introduce,

00:32:18.630 --> 00:32:20.310
the legislation he
was going to support,

00:32:20.310 --> 00:32:24.160
was based on his own
impression of what

00:32:24.160 --> 00:32:25.700
he was supposed to be doing.

00:32:25.700 --> 00:32:27.840
What was going to advance
his political career?

00:32:27.840 --> 00:32:30.440
What was the right
move for the party?

00:32:30.440 --> 00:32:33.940
Instead, he says now, he's
really much more in touch

00:32:33.940 --> 00:32:35.160
with his constituents.

00:32:35.160 --> 00:32:37.326
He's gotten out of his own
head, and he has the time

00:32:37.326 --> 00:32:41.380
to really listen to people
from Columbus and Cincinnati,

00:32:41.380 --> 00:32:42.930
the cities he represents.

00:32:42.930 --> 00:32:47.780
And he says, you
actually slow down enough

00:32:47.780 --> 00:32:50.030
to pay attention to someone
other than yourself-- more

00:32:50.030 --> 00:32:53.000
sympathetic, empathetic,
or compassionate.

00:32:53.000 --> 00:32:54.600
And it's an
extraordinary testament,

00:32:54.600 --> 00:32:57.240
and he's doing very good
work allocating resources

00:32:57.240 --> 00:32:59.780
to veterans, to schools
in his home district,

00:32:59.780 --> 00:33:03.450
trying to bring mindfulness
into schools and VA centers.

00:33:03.450 --> 00:33:05.960
So maybe a bit more
compassionate on the margins,

00:33:05.960 --> 00:33:08.856
socially responsible,
perhaps, as well-- this guy

00:33:08.856 --> 00:33:09.480
would argue so.

00:33:09.480 --> 00:33:10.490
This is Yvon Chouinard.

00:33:10.490 --> 00:33:13.590
He's the founder of Patagonia,
the apparel company,

00:33:13.590 --> 00:33:18.840
a long-time Zen Buddhist, even
before he founded Patagonia.

00:33:18.840 --> 00:33:21.800
And he created a
very unusual company.

00:33:21.800 --> 00:33:25.160
They don't necessarily teach
meditation at the Patagonia

00:33:25.160 --> 00:33:27.590
campus, even though it's
a very idyllic place.

00:33:27.590 --> 00:33:31.590
Instead, he's really
empowered his top executives

00:33:31.590 --> 00:33:34.440
to bring the attitude
of mindfulness-- mindful

00:33:34.440 --> 00:33:38.030
consumption, an awareness
of the company's impact

00:33:38.030 --> 00:33:41.310
on the planet-- into all
their business decisions.

00:33:41.310 --> 00:33:44.640
So once a year, they
run this ad that says

00:33:44.640 --> 00:33:46.430
don't buy this jacket.

00:33:46.430 --> 00:33:48.650
And it's a really
subversive thing.

00:33:48.650 --> 00:33:51.430
They're saying, you
may want this jacket.

00:33:51.430 --> 00:33:52.210
But guess what?

00:33:52.210 --> 00:33:53.660
You probably don't need it.

00:33:53.660 --> 00:33:56.370
So it's asking us just
to question ourselves.

00:33:56.370 --> 00:33:58.550
And it plays into
this broader movement

00:33:58.550 --> 00:34:00.140
called mindful
consumption, where

00:34:00.140 --> 00:34:02.440
the principles of
mindfulness are trying

00:34:02.440 --> 00:34:06.920
to be put in and adopted by
retailers, who are asking us

00:34:06.920 --> 00:34:10.330
not to consume more and more
and more, as we're want to do,

00:34:10.330 --> 00:34:12.100
but actually to
take what we need.

00:34:12.100 --> 00:34:13.469
And Yvon, I asked him.

00:34:13.469 --> 00:34:16.310
I said, this can't be
good for your business.

00:34:16.310 --> 00:34:19.699
And he said, I think we
can reach more people

00:34:19.699 --> 00:34:21.639
but sell less to
each one of them.

00:34:21.639 --> 00:34:22.400
That's his goal.

00:34:22.400 --> 00:34:25.460
He would like you to not buy
five Patagonia products a year.

00:34:25.460 --> 00:34:28.340
He'd rather you buy one
Patagonia product every five

00:34:28.340 --> 00:34:31.190
years but have a much broader
audience around the world.

00:34:31.190 --> 00:34:33.480
And that's their mission.

00:34:33.480 --> 00:34:35.710
Another example
is Eileen Fisher.

00:34:35.710 --> 00:34:38.469
She, on the other hand, was
not a long-time meditator.

00:34:38.469 --> 00:34:42.840
She developed a very successful
company-- her own brand,

00:34:42.840 --> 00:34:44.522
Eileen Fisher women's clothing.

00:34:44.522 --> 00:34:45.230
And it was great.

00:34:45.230 --> 00:34:46.360
It was a success.

00:34:46.360 --> 00:34:48.909
But she got well
into her career,

00:34:48.909 --> 00:34:50.989
and she was feeling
somewhat empty.

00:34:50.989 --> 00:34:52.280
So she started practicing yoga.

00:34:52.280 --> 00:34:54.346
She started
practicing meditation,

00:34:54.346 --> 00:34:55.929
and all of a sudden,
the world kind of

00:34:55.929 --> 00:34:58.080
opened up to her as it
did with Mark Bertolini.

00:34:58.080 --> 00:35:00.240
And she realized she
had a responsibility

00:35:00.240 --> 00:35:02.400
not only to her
employees, but also

00:35:02.400 --> 00:35:06.810
to her customers and
the environment as well.

00:35:06.810 --> 00:35:10.530
And so she started by
changing just the way

00:35:10.530 --> 00:35:11.810
things worked at the company.

00:35:11.810 --> 00:35:13.460
She did away with square tables.

00:35:13.460 --> 00:35:15.920
Everyone has meetings
in a circle now.

00:35:15.920 --> 00:35:18.690
She offered meditation
and mindfulness,

00:35:18.690 --> 00:35:20.810
did away with some of
the corporate hierarchy.

00:35:20.810 --> 00:35:21.570
And guess what?

00:35:21.570 --> 00:35:23.420
Her employees, no
surprise, loved it.

00:35:23.420 --> 00:35:26.217
But then she made that step
that Green Mountain coffee did.

00:35:26.217 --> 00:35:27.800
She said, well, what
about the workers

00:35:27.800 --> 00:35:31.230
at the very end of
my supply chain?

00:35:31.230 --> 00:35:34.320
A lot of her clothes were made
in China, and so she said,

00:35:34.320 --> 00:35:38.700
I have a responsibility
to these people as well.

00:35:38.700 --> 00:35:43.950
She started offering education,
better health care, and then

00:35:43.950 --> 00:35:46.020
women's entrepreneurship
programs,

00:35:46.020 --> 00:35:48.522
trying to get her factory
workers actually out

00:35:48.522 --> 00:35:49.230
of her factories.

00:35:49.230 --> 00:35:52.500
She wants them to start
their own businesses--

00:35:52.500 --> 00:35:54.940
and just another extraordinary
example of something

00:35:54.940 --> 00:35:58.030
Eileen says she has
done, motivated largely

00:35:58.030 --> 00:36:01.600
by her mindfulness and
meditation practice.

00:36:01.600 --> 00:36:03.960
So in some of these
examples, mindfulness

00:36:03.960 --> 00:36:10.290
has come from the top down--
Mark Bertolini, Eileen Fisher.

00:36:10.290 --> 00:36:12.599
Executives decided they
were into it, pushed it down

00:36:12.599 --> 00:36:13.390
to their employees.

00:36:13.390 --> 00:36:16.100
Other examples, like Janice
Marturano, bottom up.

00:36:16.100 --> 00:36:18.530
So mindfulness is happening
in all sorts of ways,

00:36:18.530 --> 00:36:20.390
and it's still
pretty early days.

00:36:20.390 --> 00:36:22.730
And what are some ways we
can be mindful at work?

00:36:22.730 --> 00:36:24.900
Well, we did our
sitting meditation.

00:36:24.900 --> 00:36:26.720
And bringing that same
quality of attention

00:36:26.720 --> 00:36:29.140
to eating a sandwich,
picking up the phone,

00:36:29.140 --> 00:36:32.840
or just riding the elevator
can all be effective techniques

00:36:32.840 --> 00:36:36.540
to just slow down in the middle
of our very, very busy work

00:36:36.540 --> 00:36:37.224
days.

