00:44:25.190 --> 00:44:27.120
it's really for these
young engineers,

00:44:27.120 --> 00:44:30.250
an amazing group of very
young, talented guys

00:44:30.250 --> 00:44:32.710
is San Francisco-- guys
and girls, excuse me.

00:44:32.710 --> 00:44:36.000
They are really using it to
be more focused and on the job

00:44:36.000 --> 00:44:36.950
and more productive.

00:44:36.950 --> 00:44:39.452
Because that's a
fast-moving startup up.

00:44:39.452 --> 00:44:41.910
I didn't mention them, but they
have an amazing mindfulness

00:44:41.910 --> 00:44:43.680
curriculum, working
with actually the son

00:44:43.680 --> 00:44:47.430
of Jon Kabat-Zinn, who comes
in twice a week now, to Medium.

00:44:47.430 --> 00:44:50.710
So I'm going to try
to resist being ageist

00:44:50.710 --> 00:44:53.650
and be optimistic that it's
really accessible to people

00:44:53.650 --> 00:44:56.840
on all ends of the spectrum.

00:44:56.840 --> 00:44:59.930
Another question?

00:44:59.930 --> 00:45:01.565
Yeah, Sam, is it?

00:45:01.565 --> 00:45:02.259
AUDIENCE: Sam.

00:45:02.259 --> 00:45:03.050
DAVID GELLES: Yeah.

00:45:06.520 --> 00:45:09.460
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:45:09.460 --> 00:45:11.510
I, like quite a
lot of people here,

00:45:11.510 --> 00:45:13.680
do commute quite long distances.

00:45:13.680 --> 00:45:18.810
And whilst I'm committed to
trying to introduce moments

00:45:18.810 --> 00:45:22.620
to pause whilst at work, do you
have any top tips for people

00:45:22.620 --> 00:45:24.960
who want to make the
most of that, what

00:45:24.960 --> 00:45:26.570
can be at times
quite stressful time,

00:45:26.570 --> 00:45:30.460
and transform it into one that
can be a bit more mentally

00:45:30.460 --> 00:45:31.100
nourishing?

00:45:31.100 --> 00:45:33.100
DAVID GELLES:
Absolutely, I also try

00:45:33.100 --> 00:45:36.479
to be mindful on the subway
of New York City, which

00:45:36.479 --> 00:45:38.770
at rush hour, going through
Times Square where "The New

00:45:38.770 --> 00:45:43.410
York Times" is located is
about all but impossible.

00:45:43.410 --> 00:45:45.600
And so the one that
I've been working on

00:45:45.600 --> 00:45:49.470
is actually mindful walking,
and not just focusing

00:45:49.470 --> 00:45:51.980
on the subtle
sensations of my body,

00:45:51.980 --> 00:45:54.480
but actually just being
more spatially aware.

00:45:54.480 --> 00:45:56.180
And in a very
crowded environment,

00:45:56.180 --> 00:45:59.590
I find that if I'm much
more attuned to my own body

00:45:59.590 --> 00:46:02.360
and its relation to
other people around me,

00:46:02.360 --> 00:46:03.940
I have less time to
just be caught up

00:46:03.940 --> 00:46:06.040
and be anxious and
be kind of frustrated

00:46:06.040 --> 00:46:08.800
with someone next to me and
someone pushing against me.

00:46:08.800 --> 00:46:13.220
But I actually then
move a bit more

00:46:13.220 --> 00:46:15.850
deliberately through
those crowds.

00:46:15.850 --> 00:46:19.150
And so it seems ironic to
try to be actually more

00:46:19.150 --> 00:46:22.220
aware of perhaps the last
place you'd like to be,

00:46:22.220 --> 00:46:25.186
a crowded subway, but actually
bringing my attention to it

00:46:25.186 --> 00:46:26.560
rather than just
trying to resist

00:46:26.560 --> 00:46:28.800
it is actually
counter intuitively

00:46:28.800 --> 00:46:30.790
the thing that I
find helps most.

00:46:30.790 --> 00:46:31.550
So I don't know.

00:46:31.550 --> 00:46:32.175
Give it a shot.

00:46:32.175 --> 00:46:35.960
If it doesn't work,
try Headspace, an app.

00:46:35.960 --> 00:46:37.012
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:46:37.012 --> 00:46:39.674
DAVID GELLES: Yeah, please.

00:46:39.674 --> 00:46:41.840
AUDIENCE: It kind of links
to the previous question,

00:46:41.840 --> 00:46:46.390
actually, but a lot of the
examples in that were kind of I

00:46:46.390 --> 00:46:49.150
guess people reaching
a stage in life,

00:46:49.150 --> 00:46:52.610
having a catastrophic event
or a bit of an epiphany

00:46:52.610 --> 00:46:56.360
or a life-changing moment
and kind of finding something

00:46:56.360 --> 00:46:59.230
within themselves and having
that sort of realization.

00:46:59.230 --> 00:47:01.220
With that in mind,
and sort of that

00:47:01.220 --> 00:47:03.690
being an obvious way in which
lots of people come to this--

00:47:03.690 --> 00:47:05.670
you can kind of
understand why-- how

00:47:05.670 --> 00:47:09.880
do you best share this
with people who are maybe

00:47:09.880 --> 00:47:12.430
slightly more on the
skeptic sort of scale?

00:47:12.430 --> 00:47:13.930
DAVID GELLES: It's
a great question,

00:47:13.930 --> 00:47:18.230
and I wish I had the
most easy answer.

00:47:18.230 --> 00:47:20.650
But I guess I'd say,
even if we don't

00:47:20.650 --> 00:47:22.700
have a life-changing,
catastrophic event,

00:47:22.700 --> 00:47:24.210
we're all stressed.

00:47:24.210 --> 00:47:25.930
And I think that's
why Jon Kabat-Zinn has

00:47:25.930 --> 00:47:27.930
been so successful with
mindfulness-based stress

00:47:27.930 --> 00:47:31.020
reduction-- tens of thousands of
people he's trained personally.

00:47:31.020 --> 00:47:33.800
And if you just go in
through that door-- like,

00:47:33.800 --> 00:47:34.550
are you stressed?

00:47:34.550 --> 00:47:35.820
Yes, we're all stressed.

00:47:35.820 --> 00:47:38.840
Would you like to be just
a little bit less stressed?

00:47:38.840 --> 00:47:40.310
Yeah, OK.

00:47:40.310 --> 00:47:44.160
And so even though we might
not have a catastrophe,

00:47:44.160 --> 00:47:46.970
I think we're all suffering
in these little ways that

00:47:46.970 --> 00:47:49.820
really do add up.

00:47:49.820 --> 00:47:53.210
So I don't feel like that's
entirely satisfactory answer

00:47:53.210 --> 00:47:55.600
myself, but I think
it's where we're at.

00:47:55.600 --> 00:47:58.560
And a lot of people
do respond to even

00:47:58.560 --> 00:48:02.559
those small, small changes.

00:48:02.559 --> 00:48:03.100
Yeah, please.

00:48:06.524 --> 00:48:07.940
AUDIENCE: I just
have a quick one.

00:48:07.940 --> 00:48:09.040
Thanks for the talk.

00:48:09.040 --> 00:48:12.620
So we shared a lot of tips
for informal practice.

00:48:12.620 --> 00:48:15.657
I was wondering what is
your formal practice?

00:48:15.657 --> 00:48:17.990
DAVID GELLES: My formal
practice over the last 10 months

00:48:17.990 --> 00:48:21.640
has been disrupted by a little
girl who's now 10 months old,

00:48:21.640 --> 00:48:23.020
which is amazing.

00:48:23.020 --> 00:48:27.600
And, really, she's my
greatest teacher now.

00:48:27.600 --> 00:48:31.000
How many people in
the room are parents?

00:48:31.000 --> 00:48:34.920
As you know, these little people
demand your entire presence

00:48:34.920 --> 00:48:36.160
all the time.

00:48:36.160 --> 00:48:38.480
They will not let you slip.

00:48:38.480 --> 00:48:42.810
And I catch myself
when it's 5:00 AM.

00:48:42.810 --> 00:48:43.450
She's up.

00:48:43.450 --> 00:48:46.720
She wants to party, and I'm
still fast asleep in my head.

00:48:46.720 --> 00:48:49.570
And it's so easy just
to glance at my iPhone.

00:48:49.570 --> 00:48:51.810
And so it's just every time
I find myself doing that,

00:48:51.810 --> 00:48:54.220
it's this queue to put
it down and actually just

00:48:54.220 --> 00:48:56.530
be present, be
attentive with her.

00:48:56.530 --> 00:48:59.240
So all of which is to
say, my formal practice,

00:48:59.240 --> 00:49:03.100
until 10 months ago,
involved usually

00:49:03.100 --> 00:49:04.850
in the morning--
that's when I sit best.

00:49:04.850 --> 00:49:06.770
At the end of the day,
I find I'm so wound up

00:49:06.770 --> 00:49:07.910
and I've got so many
things in my head

00:49:07.910 --> 00:49:09.020
it's a little bit harder.

00:49:09.020 --> 00:49:10.910
So for me, it tends
to be in the morning,

00:49:10.910 --> 00:49:13.850
and I would sit anywhere
from 5 to 15 minutes,

00:49:13.850 --> 00:49:17.440
during the weekday, to 50
minutes on the weekends.

00:49:17.440 --> 00:49:19.650
Now, I'd say I get to
do that kind of formal

00:49:19.650 --> 00:49:23.050
sitting practice less regularly,
a few times throughout the week

00:49:23.050 --> 00:49:23.670
maybe.

00:49:23.670 --> 00:49:27.100
But then I also have a group
of friends and professionals--

00:49:27.100 --> 00:49:29.990
bankers, TV producers,
executives in New York City.

00:49:29.990 --> 00:49:32.410
We meet a couple times
a month in the evening,

00:49:32.410 --> 00:49:34.320
and we'll sit together
and have a discussion

00:49:34.320 --> 00:49:35.460
about how things are going.

00:49:35.460 --> 00:49:38.390
And then I also go
to evening workshops

00:49:38.390 --> 00:49:42.540
at local meditation
centers in New York.

00:49:42.540 --> 00:49:46.630
And I do feel like that's
less formal practice than I

00:49:46.630 --> 00:49:47.550
might like.

00:49:47.550 --> 00:49:51.960
But having had a roughly
formal practice for 15 years,

00:49:51.960 --> 00:49:55.610
it's given me kind of
some momentum where

00:49:55.610 --> 00:49:57.660
those little moments
throughout the day

00:49:57.660 --> 00:50:02.210
are able to help maintain
some measure of equanimity.

00:50:02.210 --> 00:50:05.070
Would I like to have
kind of my daily hour

00:50:05.070 --> 00:50:06.200
where no one bothered me?

00:50:06.200 --> 00:50:08.900
Absolutely, but as a mergers
and acquisitions reporter

00:50:08.900 --> 00:50:12.110
with a 10-month-old,
not always so easy.

00:50:12.110 --> 00:50:15.310
And that's true for everyone
in this room, I'm sure.

00:50:15.310 --> 00:50:18.720
We all have very busy schedules,
so finding those little moments

00:50:18.720 --> 00:50:22.200
throughout the day, throughout
the week, are crucial.

00:50:22.200 --> 00:50:24.090
But they're possible.

00:50:24.090 --> 00:50:26.540
Any other questions?

00:50:26.540 --> 00:50:28.582
OK, oh, yeah, please.

